'''Hinduism in Wales''' is of relatively recent provenance, with under half of [[Wales|Welsh]] [[Hinduism|Hindus]] having settled there in the second half of the 20th century. There were 10,434 Hindus in Wales in the 2011 Census, almost double the number in the 2001 census.<ref>{{cite web|title=2011 Census: KS209EW Religion, local authorities in England and Wales |url=http://www.ons.gov.uk/ons/publications/re-reference-tables.html?edition=tcm%3A77-286262|publisher=ons.gov.uk|accessdate=15 December 2012}}</ref> {| class="wikitable" |- ! '''Year''' ! '''Percent''' ! '''Increase''' |- | '''2001''' | '''0.19%''' | '''-''' |- | '''2011''' | '''0.34%''' | style="background: lightgreen" | '''+0.15%''' |}
==Origins== Most Welsh Hindus are of [[India]]n origin, or at least from neighbouring countries, such as [[Sri Lanka]], [[Pakistan]], [[Nepal]] and [[Bangladesh]]. Many of these came after [[Idi Amin]]'s expulsion from [[Uganda]] in the 1970s, and some also came from [[South Africa]]. There are also a few of [[Indonesia]]n origin.
Many of these in turn are from the [[Punjab (India)|Punjab]]. Common languages amongst them, other than [[English language|English]] and [[Welsh language|Welsh]] include [[Punjabi language|Punjabi]], [[Hindi]], [[Urdu]], [[Gujarati language|Gujarati]] and [[Nepali language|Nepali]].
The Hindu Cultural Association (HCA Wales), established in March 1991, is a Registered Charity with the [[Charity Commission for England and Wales]]. It is run by the Indian community in Wales and aims to both serve the pan-Indian community as well as helping the integration of the Indian community into the wider community.<ref>[http://www.indiacentre.co.uk/aboutus.html About us] indiacentre.co.uk, accessed 22 Nov 2009</ref>
==Temples and sites== [[Skanda Vale]] is a Hindu monastic centre, based in [[Llanpumsaint]], [[Carmarthenshire]]. The site is dedicated to temple is dedicated to Lord [[Murugan|Subramanya]], and is made up of three temples. It attracts around 70,000 devotees annually.<ref>{{cite book |editor1-first=John |editor1-last=Davies|editor1-link=John Davies (historian)|editor2-first=Nigel |editor2-last=Jenkins | editor2-link=Nigel Jenkins| editor3-first=Baines |editor3-last=Menna|editor4-first=Peredur I. |editor4-last=Lynch|title=The Welsh Academy Encyclopaedia of Wales |year=2008 |publisher=University of Wales Press |location=Cardiff|page=503 |isbn=978-0-7083-1953-6}}</ref>
The largest Hindu temple in Wales, the [[Shri Swaminarayan Mandir, Cardiff|Shri Swaminarayan Mandir]], is located in [[Grangetown, Cardiff|Grangetown]], Cardiff. A [[Swaminarayan temple]] it was first opened in 1982.
The Sanatan Dharma Mandal Temple established in 1985 originally in the Parade Cardiff to serve Hindus in South Wales. Sanatan Dharma represents a code of conduct and a value system that has spiritual freedom as its core serving all Hindus within Wales and aims to offer a place of no anxiety. The temple and Hindu Community Centre is today located in the Seaview, Lewis Road, [[Splott]], Cardiff, CF24 5EB.
